        <profileDesc>
            <creation>This story, with the short title "Requested Book Copied by Saint John," is old: the earliest PEMM manuscript* in which this story appears is from around <date>1580</date>.Originally composed in <placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC3010Ethiop">Ethiopia</placeName></creation>
            <abstract>
                <p>Three priests on Mount Sinai named Dawit, Yohannes, and Elias wrote a letter to a bishop in Jerusalem asking for Mary’s book, which was rumored to be with John the Evangelist. These priests believed that John did not die, and that he continued to live on earth and perform healing miracles. When the letter arrived in Jerusalem, the members of the church searched for the book, but they could not find it. Those in Jerusalem believed that John had been killed and that Mary’s book had been destroyed when a group of Jews entered the Temple. In their letter back to Mount Sinai, the people of Jerusalem reported hearing witnesses say that Mary’s book might reside with John the son of Zebedee in Ephesus, and that they would like a copy if possible. The priests then sent a letter to Ephesus, but the church was closed. Then, after putting incense into the center of the room, they prayed to Christ. Before their prayer had ended, John appeared before them with Mary’s book. The priests later copied the book and sent it to Jerusalem.</p>
            </abstract>
